# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: marching-cubes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] A **contour line** (also **isoline**, **isopleth**, isoquant or **isarithm**) of a function of two variables is a curve along which the function has a constant value, so that the curve joins points of equal value to the state.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] It is a plane section of the three-dimensional graph of the function $f(x,y)$ parallel to the $(x,y)$ -plane.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] More generally, a contour line for a function of two variables is a curve connecting points where the function has the same particular value.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In cartography, a contour line (often just called a "contour") joins points of equal elevation (height) above a given level, such as mean sea level.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] A **contour map** is a map illustrated with contour lines, for example a topographic map, which thus shows valleys and hills, and the steepness or gentleness of slopes.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The **contour interval** of a contour map is the difference in elevation between successive contour lines.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The gradient of the function is always perpendicular to the contour lines.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] When the lines are close together the magnitude of the gradient is large: the variation is steep.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] A level set is a generalization of a contour line for functions of any number of variables.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Contour lines are curved, straight or a mixture of both lines on a map describing the intersection of a real or hypothetical surface with one or more horizontal planes.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The configuration of these contours allows map readers to infer the relative gradient of a parameter and estimate that parameter at specific places.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In the latter case, the method of interpolation affects the reliability of individual isolines and their portrayal of slope, pits and peaks.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The idea of lines that join points of equal value was rediscovered several times.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The oldest known isobath (contour line of constant depth) is found on a map dated 1584 of the river Spaarne, near Haarlem, by Dutchman Pieter Bruinsz.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In 1701, Edmond Halley used such lines (isogons) on a chart of magnetic variation.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The Dutch engineer Nicholas Cruquius drew the bed of the river Merwede with lines of equal depth (isobaths) at intervals of 1 fathom in 1727, and Philippe Buache used them at 10-fathom intervals on a chart of the English Channel that was prepared in 1737 and published in 1752.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Such lines were used to describe a land surface (contour lines) in a map of the Duchy of Modena and Reggio by Domenico Vandelli in 1746, and they were studied theoretically by Ducarla in 1771, and Charles Hutton used them in the Schiehallion experiment.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Dupain-Triel used contour lines at 20-metre intervals, hachures, spot-heights and a vertical section.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In 1801, the chief of the French Corps of Engineers, Haxo, used contour lines at the larger scale of 1:500 on a plan of his projects for Rocca d'Anfo, now in northern Italy, under Napoleon.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] By around 1843, when the Ordnance Survey started to regularly record contour lines in Great Britain and Ireland, they were already in general use in European countries.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Isobaths were not routinely used on nautical charts until those of Russia from 1834, and those of Britain from 1838.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] As different uses of the technique were invented independently, cartographers began to recognize a common theme, and debated what to call these "lines of equal value" generally.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The word *isogram* (from Ancient Greek ἴσος*(isos)* 'equal' and γράμμα*(gramma)* 'writing, drawing') was proposed by Francis Galton in 1889 for lines indicating equality of some physical condition or quantity, though *isogram* can also refer to a word without a repeated letter.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Wright still preferred *isogram*, but it never attained wide usage.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] During the early 20th century, *isopleth* (πλῆθος, *plethos*, 'amount') was being used by 1911 in the United States, while *isarithm* (ἀριθμός, *arithmos*, 'number') had become common in Europe.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Additional alternatives, including the Greek-English hybrid *isoline* and *isometric line* (μέτρον, *metron*, 'measure'), also emerged.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Despite attempts to select a single standard, all of these alternatives have survived to the present.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] When maps with contour lines became common, the idea spread to other applications.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Perhaps the latest to develop are air quality and noise pollution contour maps, which first appeared in the United States in approximately 1970, largely as a result of national legislation requiring spatial delineation of these parameters.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Contour lines are often given specific names beginning with "*iso-*" according to the nature of the variable being mapped, although in many usages the phrase "contour line" is most commonly used.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Specific names are most common in meteorology, where multiple maps with different variables may be viewed simultaneously.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The prefix "'*iso-*" can be replaced with "*isallo-*" to specify a contour line connecting points where a variable changes at the same *rate* during a given time period.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isogon** (from Ancient Greek γωνία*(gonia)* 'angle') is a contour line for a variable which measures direction.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In meteorology and in geomagnetics, the term *isogon* has specific meanings which are described below.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isocline** (κλίνειν, *klinein*, 'to lean or slope') is a line joining points with equal slope.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In population dynamics and in geomagnetics, the terms *isocline* and *isoclinic line* have specific meanings which are described below.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] A curve of equidistant points is a set of points all at the same distance from a given point, line, or polyline.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In this case the function whose value is being held constant along a contour line is a distance function.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An example of an isopleth is population density, which can be calculated by dividing the population of a census district by the surface area of that district.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Each calculated value is presumed to be the value of the variable at the centre of the area, and isopleths can then be drawn by a process of interpolation.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The idea of an isopleth map can be compared with that of a choropleth map.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In meteorology, the word *isopleth* is used for any type of contour line.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Meteorological contour lines are based on interpolation of the point data received from weather stations and weather satellites.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Weather stations are seldom exactly positioned at a contour line (when they are, this indicates a measurement precisely equal to the value of the contour).
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Instead, lines are drawn to best approximate the locations of exact values, based on the scattered information points available.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Meteorological contour maps may present collected data such as actual air pressure at a given time, or generalized data such as average pressure over a period of time, or forecast data such as predicted air pressure at some point in the future.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Thermodynamic diagrams use multiple overlapping contour sets (including isobars and isotherms) to present a picture of the major thermodynamic factors in a weather system.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isobar** (from Ancient Greek βάρος*(baros)* 'weight') is a line of equal or constant pressure on a graph, plot, or map; an isopleth or contour line of pressure.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] More accurately, isobars are lines drawn on a map joining places of equal average atmospheric pressure reduced to sea level for a specified period of time.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In meteorology, the barometric pressures shown are reduced to sea level, not the surface pressures at the map locations.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The distribution of isobars is closely related to the magnitude and direction of the wind field, and can be used to predict future weather patterns.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Isobars are commonly used in television weather reporting.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An isopycnal is a line of constant density.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An *isoheight* or *isohypse* is a line of constant geopotential height on a constant pressure surface chart.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Isohypse and isoheight are simply known as lines showing equal pressure on a map.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isotherm** (from Ancient Greek θέρμη*(thermē)* 'heat') is a line that connects points on a map that have the same temperature.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Therefore, all points through which an isotherm passes have the same or equal temperatures at the time indicated.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An isotherm at 0 °C is called the freezing level.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The term *lignes isothermes* (or *lignes d'égale chaleur)* was coined by the Prussian geographer and naturalist Alexander von Humboldt, who as part of his research into the geographical distribution of plants published the first map of isotherms in Paris, in 1817.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] According to Thomas Hankins, the Scottish engineer William Playfair's graphical developments greatly influenced Alexander von Humbolt's invention of the isotherm.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Humbolt later used his visualizations and analyses to contradict theories by Kant and other Enlightenment thinkers that non-Europeans were inferior due to their climate.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isocheim** is a line of equal mean winter temperature, and an **isothere** is a line of equal mean summer temperature.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isohel** (ἥλιος, *helios*, 'Sun') is a line of equal or constant solar radiation.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isogeotherm** is a line of equal temperature beneath the Earth's surface.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isohyet** or **isohyetal line** (from Ancient Greek ὑετός*(huetos)* 'rain') is a line on a map joining points of equal rainfall in a given period.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] A map with isohyets is called an **isohyetal map**.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isohume** is a line of constant relative humidity, while an **isodrosotherm** (from Ancient Greek δρόσος*(drosos)* 'dew' and θέρμη*(therme)* 'heat') is a line of equal or constant dew point.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isoneph** is a line indicating equal cloud cover.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isochalaz** is a line of constant frequency of hail storms, and an **isobront** is a line drawn through geographical points at which a given phase of thunderstorm activity occurred simultaneously.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Snow cover is frequently shown as a contour-line map.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isotach** (from Ancient Greek ταχύς*(tachus)* 'fast') is a line joining points with constant wind speed.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In meteorology, the term **isogon** refers to a line of constant wind direction.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isopectic** line denotes equal dates of ice formation each winter, and an **isotac** denotes equal dates of thawing.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Contours are one of several common methods used to denote elevation or altitude and depth on maps.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] From these contours, a sense of the general terrain can be determined.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] They are used at a variety of scales, from large-scale engineering drawings and architectural plans, through topographic maps and bathymetric charts, up to continental-scale maps.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] "Contour line" is the most common usage in cartography, but isobath for underwater depths on bathymetric maps and **isohypse** for elevations are also used.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In cartography, the **contour interval** is the elevation difference between adjacent contour lines.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The contour interval should be the same over a single map.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] When calculated as a ratio against the map scale, a sense of the hilliness of the terrain can be derived.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Of course, to determine differences in elevation between two points, the contour interval, or distance in altitude between two adjacent contour lines, must be known, and this is normally stated in the map key.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Usually contour intervals are consistent throughout a map, but there are exceptions.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Sometimes intermediate contours are present in flatter areas; these can be dashed or dotted lines at half the noted contour interval.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] When contours are used with hypsometric tints on a small-scale map that includes mountains and flatter low-lying areas, it is common to have smaller intervals at lower elevations so that detail is shown in all areas.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Conversely, for an island which consists of a plateau surrounded by steep cliffs, it is possible to use smaller intervals as the height increases.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isopotential map** is a measure of electrostatic potential in space, often depicted in two dimensions with the electrostatic charges inducing that electric potential.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The term **equipotential line** or **isopotential line** refers to a curve of constant electric potential.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Whether crossing an equipotential line represents ascending or descending the potential is inferred from the labels on the charges.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In three dimensions, **equipotential surfaces** may be depicted with a two dimensional cross-section, showing equipotential lines at the intersection of the surfaces and the cross-section.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The general mathematical term level set is often used to describe the full collection of points having a particular potential, especially in higher dimensional space.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In the study of the Earth's magnetic field, the term **isogon** or **isogonic line** refers to a line of constant magnetic declination, the variation of magnetic north from geographic north.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **agonic line** is drawn through points of zero magnetic declination.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isoporic line** refers to a line of constant annual variation of magnetic declination .
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isoclinic line** connects points of equal magnetic dip, and an **aclinic line** is the isoclinic line of magnetic dip zero.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isodynamic line** (from δύναμις or *dynamis* meaning 'power') connects points with the same intensity of magnetic force.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Besides ocean depth, oceanographers use contour to describe diffuse variable phenomena much as meteorologists do with atmospheric phenomena.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In particular, **isobathytherms** are lines showing depths of water with equal temperature, **isohalines** show lines of equal ocean salinity, and **isopycnals** are surfaces of equal water density.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Various geological data are rendered as contour maps in structural geology, sedimentology, stratigraphy and economic geology.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Contour maps are used to show the below ground surface of geologic strata, fault surfaces (especially low angle thrust faults) and unconformities.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Isopach maps use **isopachs** (lines of equal thickness) to illustrate variations in thickness of geologic units.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In discussing pollution, density maps can be very useful in indicating sources and areas of greatest contamination.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Contour maps are especially useful for diffuse forms or scales of pollution.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Acid precipitation is indicated on maps with **isoplats**.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Some of the most widespread applications of environmental science contour maps involve mapping of environmental noise (where lines of equal sound pressure level are denoted **isobels**), air pollution, soil contamination, thermal pollution and groundwater contamination.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] By contour planting and contour ploughing, the rate of water runoff and thus soil erosion can be substantially reduced; this is especially important in riparian zones.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isoflor** is an isopleth contour connecting areas of comparable biological diversity.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Usually, the variable is the number of species of a given genus or family that occurs in a region.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Isoflor maps are thus used to show distribution patterns and trends such as centres of diversity.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In economics, contour lines can be used to describe features which vary quantitatively over space.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isochrone** shows lines of equivalent drive time or travel time to a given location and is used in the generation of isochrone maps.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isotim** shows equivalent transport costs from the source of a raw material, and an **isodapane** shows equivalent cost of travel time.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Contour lines are also used to display non-geographic information in economics.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] **Indifference curves** (as shown at left) are used to show bundles of goods to which a person would assign equal utility.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] An **isoquant** (in the image at right) is a curve of equal production quantity for alternative combinations of input usages, and an **isocost curve** (also in the image at right) shows alternative usages having equal production costs.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In political science an analogous method is used in understanding coalitions (for example the diagram in Laver and Shepsle's work).
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In population dynamics, an **isocline** shows the set of population sizes at which the rate of change, or partial derivative, for one population in a pair of interacting populations is zero.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In statistics, isodensity lines or isodensanes are lines that join points with the same value of a probability density.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Isodensanes are used to display bivariate distributions.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] For example, for a bivariate elliptical distribution the isodensity lines are ellipses.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Various types of graphs in thermodynamics, engineering, and other sciences use isobars (constant pressure), isotherms (constant temperature), isochors (constant specific volume), or other types of isolines, even though these graphs are usually not related to maps.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Such isolines are useful for representing more than two dimensions (or quantities) on two-dimensional graphs.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Common examples in thermodynamics are some types of phase diagrams.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In interpreting radar images, an **isodop** is a line of equal Doppler velocity, and an **isoecho** is a line of equal radar reflectivity.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In the case of hybrid contours, energies of hybrid orbitals and the energies of pure atomic orbitals are plotted.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The graph obtained is called hybrid contour.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] To maximize readability of contour maps, there are several design choices available to the map creator, principally line weight, line color, line type and method of numerical marking.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] If the contour lines are not numerically labeled and adjacent lines have the same style (with the same weight, color and type), then the direction of the gradient cannot be determined from the contour lines alone.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] However, if the contour lines cycle through three or more styles, then the direction of the gradient can be determined from the lines.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] The orientation of the numerical text labels is often used to indicate the direction of the slope.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Most commonly contour lines are drawn in plan view, or as an observer in space would view the Earth's surface: ordinary map form.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] However, some parameters can often be displayed in profile view showing a vertical profile of the parameter mapped.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Some of the most common parameters mapped in profile are air pollutant concentrations and sound levels.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In each of those cases it may be important to analyze (air pollutant concentrations or sound levels) at varying heights so as to determine the air quality or noise health effects on people at different elevations, for example, living on different floor levels of an urban apartment.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] In actuality, both plan and profile view contour maps are used in air pollution and noise pollution studies.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Labels are a critical component of elevation maps.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] A properly labeled contour map helps the reader to quickly interpret the shape of the terrain.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] If numbers are placed close to each other, it means that the terrain is steep.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Labels should be placed along a slightly curved line "pointing" to the summit or nadir, from several directions if possible, making the visual identification of the summit or nadir easy.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Contour labels can be oriented so a reader is facing uphill when reading the label.
[src:marching-cubes/contour-line] Manual labeling of contour maps is a time-consuming process, however, there are a few software systems that can do the job automatically and in accordance with cartographic conventions, called automatic label placement.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] An **isosurface** is a three-dimensional analog of an isoline.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] It is a surface that represents points of a constant value (e.g. pressure, temperature, velocity, density) within a volume of space; in other words, it is a level set of a continuous function whose domain is 3-space.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] The term *isoline* is also sometimes used for domains of more than 3 dimensions.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] Isosurfaces are normally displayed using computer graphics, and are used as data visualization methods in computational fluid dynamics (CFD), allowing engineers to study features of a fluid flow (gas or liquid) around objects, such as aircraft wings.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] An isosurface may represent an individual shock wave in supersonic flight, or several isosurfaces may be generated showing a sequence of pressure values in the air flowing around a wing.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] Isosurfaces tend to be a popular form of visualization for volume datasets since they can be rendered by a simple polygonal model, which can be drawn on the screen very quickly.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] In medical imaging, isosurfaces may be used to represent regions of a particular density in a three-dimensional CT scan, allowing the visualization of internal organs, bones, or other structures.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] Numerous other disciplines that are interested in three-dimensional data often use isosurfaces to obtain information about pharmacology, chemistry, geophysics and meteorology.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] The marching cubes algorithm was first published in the 1987 SIGGRAPH proceedings by Lorensen and Cline, and it creates a surface by intersecting the edges of a data volume grid with the volume contour.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] Where the surface intersects the edge the algorithm creates a vertex.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] By using a table of different triangles depending on different patterns of edge intersections the algorithm can create a surface.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] This algorithm has solutions for implementation both on the CPU and on the GPU.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] The asymptotic decider algorithm was developed as an extension to marching cubes in order to resolve the possibility of ambiguity in it.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] The marching tetrahedra algorithm was developed as an extension to marching cubes in order to solve an ambiguity in that algorithm and to create higher quality output surface.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] The Surface Nets algorithm places an intersecting vertex in the middle of a volume voxel instead of at the edges, leading to a smoother output surface.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] The dual contouring algorithm was first published in the 2002 SIGGRAPH proceedings by Ju and Losasso, developed as an extension to both surface nets and marching cubes.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] It retains a dual vertex within the voxel but no longer at the center.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] Dual contouring leverages the position and normal of where the surface crosses the edges of a voxel to interpolate the position of the dual vertex within the voxel.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] This has the benefit of retaining sharp or smooth surfaces where surface nets often look blocky or incorrectly beveled.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] Dual contouring often uses surface generation that leverages octrees as an optimization to adapt the number of triangles in output to the complexity of the surface.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] Examples of isosurfaces are 'Metaballs' or 'blobby objects' used in 3D visualisation.
[src:marching-cubes/isosurface] A more general way to construct an isosurface is to use the function representation.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] When the number of independent variables is two, a level set is called a **level curve**, also known as *contour line* or *isoline*; so a level curve is the set of all real-valued solutions of an equation in two variables *x*1 and *x*2.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] When *n* = 3, a level set is called a **level surface** (or *isosurface*); so a level surface is the set of all real-valued roots of an equation in three variables *x*1, *x*2 and *x*3.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] For higher values of n, the level set is a **level hypersurface**, the set of all real-valued roots of an equation in *n* > 3 variables (a higher-dimensional hypersurface).
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] A level set is a special case of a fiber.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] Level sets show up in many applications, often under different names.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] For example, an implicit curve is a level curve, which is considered independently of its neighbor curves, emphasizing that such a curve is defined by an implicit equation.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] Analogously, a level surface is sometimes called an implicit surface or an isosurface.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] The name isocontour is also used, which means a contour of equal height.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] In various application areas, isocontours have received specific names, which indicate often the nature of the values of the considered function, such as isobar, isotherm, isogon, isochrone, isoquant and indifference curve.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] Consider the 2-dimensional Euclidean distance: $d(x,y)={\sqrt {x^{2}+y^{2}}}$ A level set $L_{r}(d)$ of this function consists of those points that lie at a distance of r from the origin, that make a circle.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] Geometrically, this means that the point $(3,4)$ lies on the circle of radius 5 centered at the origin.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] More generally, a sphere in a metric space $(M,m)$ with radius r centered at $x\in M$ can be defined as the level set $L_{r}(y\mapsto m(x,y))$ .
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] A second example is the plot of Himmelblau's function shown in the figure to the right.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] Each curve shown is a level curve of the function, and they are spaced logarithmically: if a curve represents $L_{x}$ , the curve directly "within" represents $L_{x/10}$ , and the curve directly "outside" represents $L_{10x}$ .
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] To understand what this means, imagine that two hikers are at the same location on a mountain.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] One of them is bold, and decides to go in the direction where the slope is steepest.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] The other one is more cautious and does not want to either climb or descend, choosing a path which stays at the same height.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] In our analogy, the above theorem says that the two hikers will depart in directions perpendicular to each other.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] A consequence of this theorem (and its proof) is that if f is differentiable, a level set is a hypersurface and a manifold outside the critical points of f.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] At a critical point, a level set may be reduced to a point (for example at a local extremum of f ) or may have a singularity such as a self-intersection point or a cusp.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] is called a **sublevel set** of *f* (or, alternatively, a **lower level set** or **trench** of *f*).
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] is called a **superlevel set** of *f* (or, alternatively, an **upper level set** of *f*).
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] Sublevel sets are important in minimization theory.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] By Weierstrass's theorem, the boundness of some non-empty sublevel set and the lower-semicontinuity of the function implies that a function attains its minimum.
[src:marching-cubes/level-set] The convexity of all the sublevel sets characterizes quasiconvex functions.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] The algorithm was developed by William E.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Cline as a result of their research for General Electric.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] At General Electric they worked on a way to efficiently visualize data from CT and MRI devices.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] The premise of the algorithm is to divide the input volume into a discrete set of cubes.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] By assuming linear reconstruction filtering, each cube, which contains a piece of a given isosurface, can easily be identified because the sample values at the cube vertices must span the target isosurface value.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] For each cube containing a section of the isosurface, a triangular mesh that approximates the behavior of the trilinear interpolant in the interior cube is generated.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] The first published version of the algorithm exploited rotational and reflective symmetry and also sign changes to build the table with 15 unique cases.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] However, due to the existence of ambiguities in the trilinear interpolant behavior in the cube faces and interior, the meshes extracted by the Marching Cubes presented discontinuities and topological issues.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Given a cube of the grid, a face ambiguity occurs when its face vertices have alternating signs.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] That is, the vertices of one diagonal on this face are positive and the vertices on the other are negative.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Observe that in this case, the signs of the face vertices are insufficient to determine the correct way to triangulate the isosurface.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Similarly, an interior ambiguity occurs when the signs of the cube vertices are insufficient to determine the correct surface triangulation, i.e., when multiple triangulations are possible for the same cube configuration.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] The popularity of the Marching Cubes and its widespread adoption resulted in several improvements in the algorithm to deal with the ambiguities and to correctly track the behavior of the interpolant.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Durst in 1988 was the first to note that the triangulation table proposed by Lorensen and Cline was incomplete, and that certain Marching Cubes cases allow multiple triangulations.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Durst's 'additional reference' was to an earlier, more efficient (see de Araujo) isosurface polygonization algorithm by Wyvill, Wyvill and McPheeters.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Later, Nielson and Hamann in 1991 observed the existence of ambiguities in the interpolant behavior on the face of the cube.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] They proposed a test called Asymptotic Decider to correctly track the interpolant on the faces of the cube.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] In fact, as observed by Natarajan in 1994, this ambiguity problem also occurs inside the cube.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] In his work, the author proposed a disambiguation test based on the interpolant critical points, and added four new cases to the Marching Cubes triangulation table (subcases of the cases 3, 4, 6 and 7).
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] At this point, even with all the improvements proposed to the algorithm and its triangulation table, the meshes generated by the Marching Cubes still had topological incoherencies.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] The Marching Cubes 33, proposed by Chernyaev in 1995, is one of the first isosurface extraction algorithms intended to preserve the topology of the trilinear interpolant.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] In his work, Chernyaev extends to 33 the number of cases in the triangulation lookup table.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] He then proposes a different approach to solve the interior ambiguities, which is based on the Asymptotic Decider.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Later, in 2003, Nielson proved that Chernyaev's lookup table is complete and can represent all the possible behaviors of the trilinear interpolant, and Lewiner et al. proposed an implementation to the algorithm.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Also in 2003 Lopes and Brodlie extended the tests proposed by Natarajan.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] In 2013, Custodio et al. noted and corrected algorithmic inaccuracies that compromised the topological correctness of the mesh generated by the Marching Cubes 33 algorithm proposed by Chernyaev.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] The algorithm proceeds through the scalar field, taking eight neighbor locations at a time (thus forming an imaginary cube), then determining the polygon(s) needed to represent the part of the isosurface that passes through this cube.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] The individual polygons are then fused into the desired surface.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] This is done by creating an index to a precalculated array of 256 possible polygon configurations (28=256) within the cube, by treating each of the 8 scalar values as a bit in an 8-bit integer.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] If the scalar's value is higher than the iso-value (i.e., it is inside the surface) then the appropriate bit is set to one, while if it is lower (outside), it is set to zero.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] The final value, after all eight scalars are checked, is the actual index to the polygon indices array.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Finally each vertex of the generated polygons is placed on the appropriate position along the cube's edge by linearly interpolating the two scalar values that are connected by that edge.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] The gradient of the scalar field at each grid point is also the normal vector of a hypothetical isosurface passing from that point.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Therefore, these normals may be interpolated along the edges of each cube to find the normals of the generated vertices which are essential for shading the resulting mesh with some illumination model.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] An implementation of the marching cubes algorithm was patented as United States Patent 4,710,876.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] Another similar algorithm was developed, called marching tetrahedra, in order to circumvent the patent as well as solve a minor ambiguity problem of marching cubes with some cube configurations.
[src:marching-cubes/marching-cubes] The patent expired in 2005, and it is now legal for the graphics community to use it without royalties since more than the 20 years have passed from its issue date (December 1, 1987).
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] In mathematics and physics, a **scalar field** is a function associating a single number to each point in a region of space – possibly physical space.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] The scalar may either be a pure mathematical number (dimensionless) or a scalar physical quantity (with units).
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] In a physical context, scalar fields are required to be independent of the choice of reference frame.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] That is, any two observers using the same units will agree on the value of the scalar field at the same absolute point in space (or spacetime) regardless of their respective points of origin.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] Examples used in physics include the temperature distribution throughout space, the pressure distribution in a fluid, and spin-zero quantum fields, such as the Higgs field.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] These fields are the subject of scalar field theory.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] Mathematically, a scalar field on a region *U* is a real or complex-valued function or distribution on *U*.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] The region *U* may be a set in some Euclidean space, Minkowski space, or more generally a subset of a manifold, and it is typical in mathematics to impose further conditions on the field, such that it be continuous or often continuously differentiable to some order.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] A scalar field is a tensor field of order zero, and the term "scalar field" may be used to distinguish a function of this kind with a more general tensor field, density, or differential form.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] Physically, a scalar field is additionally distinguished by having units of measurement associated with it.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] In this context, a scalar field should also be independent of the coordinate system used to describe the physical system—that is, any two observers using the same units must agree on the numerical value of a scalar field at any given point of physical space.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] Scalar fields are contrasted with other physical quantities such as vector fields, which associate a vector to every point of a region, as well as tensor fields and spinor fields.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] More subtly, scalar fields are often contrasted with pseudoscalar fields.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] In physics, scalar fields often describe the potential energy associated with a particular force.
[src:marching-cubes/scalar-field] The force is a vector field, which can be obtained as a factor of the gradient of the potential energy scalar field.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] The function has positive values at points *x* inside Ω, it decreases in value as *x* approaches the boundary of Ω where the signed distance function is zero, and it takes negative values outside of Ω.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] However, the alternative convention is also sometimes taken instead (i.e., negative inside Ω and positive outside).
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] The concept also sometimes goes by the name **oriented distance function/field**.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] Let Ω be a subset of a metric space *X* with metric *d*, and $\partial \Omega$ be its boundary.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] If the boundary of Ω is *C**k* for *k* ≥ 2 (see Differentiability classes) then *d* is *C**k* on points sufficiently close to the boundary of Ω.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] where *N* is the inward normal vector field.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] The signed distance function is thus a differentiable extension of the normal vector field.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] In particular, the Hessian of the signed distance function on the boundary of Ω gives the Weingarten map.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] If, further, Γ is a region sufficiently close to the boundary of Ω that *f* is twice continuously differentiable on it, then there is an explicit formula involving the Weingarten map *W**x* for the Jacobian of changing variables in terms of the signed distance function and nearest boundary point.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] where det denotes the determinant and *dS**u* indicates that we are taking the surface integral.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] Algorithms for calculating the signed distance function include the efficient fast marching method, fast sweeping method and the more general level-set method.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] For voxel rendering, a fast algorithm for calculating the SDF in taxicab geometry uses summed-area tables.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] Signed distance functions are applied, for example, in real-time rendering, for instance the method of SDF ray marching, and computer vision.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] SDF has been used to describe object geometry in real-time rendering, usually in a raymarching context, starting in the mid 2000s.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] By 2007, Valve was using SDFs to render large pixel-size (or high DPI) smooth fonts with GPU acceleration in its games.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] Valve's method is not perfect as it runs in raster space in order to avoid the computational complexity of solving the problem in the (continuous) vector space.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] The rendered text often loses sharp corners.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] In 2014, an improved method was presented by Behdad Esfahbod.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] Behdad's GLyphy approximates the font's Bézier curves with arc splines, accelerated by grid-based discretization techniques (which culls too-far-away points) to run in real time.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] A modified version of SDF was introduced as a loss function to minimise the error in interpenetration of pixels while rendering multiple objects.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] In particular, for any pixel that does not belong to an object, if it lies outside the object in rendition, no penalty is imposed; if it does, a positive value proportional to its distance inside the object is imposed.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] In 2020, the FOSS game engine Godot 4.0 received SDF-based real-time global illumination (SDFGI), that became a compromise between more realistic voxel-based GI and baked GI.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] Its core advantage is that it can be applied to infinite space, which allows developers to use it for open-world games.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] In 2023, the authors of the Zed text editor announced a GPUI framework that draws all UI elements using the GPU at 120 fps.
[src:marching-cubes/signed-distance-function] The work makes use of Inigo Quilez's list of geometric primitives in SDF, Figma co-founder Evan Wallace's Gaussian blur in SDF, and a new rounded rectangle SDF.
